indicator.description:
1.1. Detailed inventory of PCB containing and contaminated equipment in service, existing PCB waste stockpiles and PCB contaminated sites in place in 2012;
1.2. Data management and mapping system operational and used for reporting in 2012;
1.3. Supply of 250 screening test kits and 4 portable analytical units with 10 personnel trained in their use by 2012;
1.4. Technical instructions for identification, sampling, maintenance, storage and disposal of PCB containing equipment in service and out of operation are in place in 2012;
1.5. Publically accessible information on PCBs and their management including: i) a maintained official website; ii) distributed brochures; iii) media exposure (two annual campaigns during the project implementation); iv) information events (two during the project implementation);
1.6. Training and information seminars on chemicals management including PCBs for relevant government agencies, the academic community, affected communities, NGOs and holders of PCBs (4 events during the project).
2.1. Normative documents requiring registration, labeling and status reporting of potential all PCB and PCB containing materials in use in 2012;
2.2. The classification has already been adopted and approved by the government;
2.3. Establishment of Maximum Allowable Concentrations for PCBs in environmental media, consistent with international standards in 2012;
2.4. Enactment of legal ban on new use, re- sue, trade, import and export of PCBs and PCB contaminated equipment and materials 2013;
2.5. Legal measures allowing unrestricted regulatory access to information and locations that may have PCBs (wastes, stockpiles, PCB containing equipment and site contamination) in 2012.
3.1. Basic national analytical capacity to analyze for PCBs operational with upgraded equipment installed and trained personnel in place (10 persons) by 2013;
3.2. Strategy and plan for pre-treatment and disposal of PCB stockpiles and wastes in place in 2012.
4.1. Secure storage capacity

baseline.comment:
1.1. Incomplete inventory of in-service equipment and inventories of PCB waste stockpiles, cross-contaminated equipment and contaminated sites;
1.2. There is no formal consolidated PCB Information System or associated reporting capability;
1.3. Absence of capability to cost- effectively identify and categorize PCB contaminated materials acting as a major barrier to inventory development;
1.4. No consolidated guidance available to holders of PCBs, relevant authorities or service providers on the practical primary management of PCBs;
1.5. Low level of general awareness related to PCBs and chemicals management generally across all stakeholders. 
No current information products or programs;
1.6. Key stakeholders generally have limited awareness of the issue or actions required of them to address it.
2.1. No current regulations requiring declaration /reporting / unique identification by holders of present PCB wastes and stockpiles or PCB containing equipment;
2.2. PCB waste classification is not well defined in current waste management regulations allowing potential avoidance of proper management;
2.3. MACs for PCBs in main environmental media are either not defined or can be practically applied;
2.4. No regulations on PCB trade, use and import/ export.
Uncontrolled trade in contaminated PCB equipment occurs including export of stockpiles and waste and import of used PCB equipment. Re-use of PCBs occurs. Declassification of PCB contaminated equipment occurs;
2.5. Legal barriers on the ability of authorities to access, inspect and access sites.
3.1. At present, no laboratory is equipped to specifically undertake PCB analysis, although some facilities offer an opportunity to be upgraded; 
3.2. No plan in place to develop or access pre-treatment or disposal capacity exists for PCB waste stockpiles.
4.1. No hazardous waste storage suitable for PCB waste stockpiles is available. Temporary facilities for obsolete pesticides established but with no long-term operational structu

target.comment:
1.1 Comprehensive PCB inventory for in-service equipment, waste stockpiles and contaminated sites to be maintained on an on-going basis;
1.2 Publicly accessible and government owned PCB information system is operational, maintained and used for reporting and information exchange;
1.3 Widely accessible current information on PCBs and ongoing management activities;
2.1 A comprehensive national regulatory registry of all PCB containing equipment to be tracked;
3.1 One accredited nationla laboratory capable of supplying accurate and reliable results;
3.2 Comprehensive plan adopted, defining milestones and process of PCBs phasing out in the country
4.1 One nationally designated secure storage facility established and equipped with necessary infrastructure for PCB waste stockpiles under continuing care and custody of a reponsible government authority;
4.2 Major holders have secure storage facilities to accomodate PCM contaminated equipment when retired as an option;
4.3 Established feasibility of environmentally sound transformer decontamination locally as an option to replacement and export of large volumes of materials for ESM disposal and developed LCM for sounf handling and planning.

actual.comment:
1.1. The PCB inventory activities across the country employed 255 major energy enterprises. PCB samples from 52 energy enterprises that were found to be potentially PCB containing were submitted to the laboratory for further determination of PCB concentration. Due to the absence of reference materials, the analysis was postponed to the first quarter of 2015;
1.2. A web page on Environmental Statistics has been integrated under the major website of the National Statistical Committee, which will reflect the dynamics of PCB equipment management as a special kind of industrial waste (http://sreda.geek-tar.ru/).
1.3 Still limited information on PCBs as it is linked with the laboratory test results and it will be continued in 2015;
2.1. Regulation for safe management and disposal of PCB equipment were approved by the order of the Ministry of Energy and Industry as of September 10, 2014 and circulated to all the state owned energy enterprises for further adoption and follow-up; 
3.1. Technical capacity of the laboratory under the State Agency on Environment Protection Forestry is being technically strengthened via procurement and installation of a gas chromatograph. The actual delivery of the equipment and follow-up laboratory staff trainings are scheduled for early January 2015. (there was a delay in delivery of the equipment by the supplier). This activity will enhance the country's capacity in identification and reference tests of the PCB materials and equipment.  
3.3. Initial review of relevant and needed documents for accreditation of the Laboratory under the Ministry of Health is completed. The step ahead is searching for a internationally certified reference laboratory elsewhere. So far, market research has revealed that these laboratories are located in Europe, North America and Canada. The reference exchange activity is scheduled for first quarter of 2015.
